# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: consistent-hashing-algo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] In computer science, **consistent hashing** is a special kind of hashing technique such that when a hash table is resized, only $n/m$ keys need to be remapped on average where n is the number of keys and m is the number of slots.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing evenly distributes cache keys across shards, even if some of the shards crash or become unavailable.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] In contrast, in most traditional hash tables, a change in the number of array slots causes nearly all keys to be remapped because the mapping between the keys and the slots is defined by a modular operation.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is used by Content Delivery Networks because it is useful for distributing requests for content from a rotating population of web servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Tim Berners-Lee credits consistent hashing algorithms, and Daniel Lewin as their inventor, with solving the slashdotting problem which plagued the World Wide Web in the 1990s.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] The term "consistent hashing" was introduced by David Karger *et al.* at MIT for use in distributed caching, particularly for the web.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] This academic paper from 1997 in Symposium on Theory of Computing introduced the term "consistent hashing" as a way of distributing requests among a changing population of web servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Each slot is then represented by a server in a distributed system or cluster.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] The addition of a server and the removal of a server (during scalability or outage) requires only $num\_keys/num\_slots$ items to be re-shuffled when the number of slots (i.e. servers) change.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] The authors mention linear hashing and its ability to handle sequential server addition and removal, while consistent hashing allows servers to be added and removed in an arbitrary order.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] The paper was later re-purposed to address technical challenge of keeping track of a file in peer-to-peer networks such as a distributed hash table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Teradata used this technique in their distributed database, released in 1986, although they did not use this term.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Teradata still uses the concept of a hash table to fulfill exactly this purpose.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Akamai Technologies was founded in 1998 by the scientists Daniel Lewin and F.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Thomson Leighton (co-authors of the article coining "consistent hashing").
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] In Akamai's content delivery network, consistent hashing is used to balance the load within a cluster of servers, while a stable marriage algorithm is used to balance load across clusters.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing has also been used to reduce the impact of partial system failures in large web applications to provide robust caching without incurring the system-wide fallout of a failure.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is also the cornerstone of distributed hash tables (DHTs), which employ hash values to partition a keyspace across a distributed set of nodes, then construct an overlay network of connected nodes that provide efficient node retrieval by key.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] It achieves the goals of consistent hashing using the very different highest random weight (HRW) algorithm.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] However, when a server is added or removed during outage or scaling (when n changes), all the BLOBs in every server should be reassigned and moved due to rehashing, but this operation is expensive.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing was designed to avoid the problem of having to reassign every BLOB when a server is added or removed throughout the cluster.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] The central idea is to use a hash function that maps both the BLOB and servers to a unit circle, usually $2\pi$ radians.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] For example, $\zeta =\Phi \ \%\ 360$ (where $\Phi$ is hash of a BLOB or server's identifier, like IP address or UUID).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Each BLOB is then assigned to the next server that appears on the circle in clockwise order.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] This provides an even distribution of BLOBs to servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] But, more importantly, if a server fails and is removed from the circle, only the BLOBs that were mapped to the failed server need to be reassigned to the next server in clockwise order.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Likewise, if a new server is added, it is added to the unit circle, and only the BLOBs mapped to that server need to be reassigned.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Importantly, when a server is added or removed, the vast majority of the BLOBs maintain their prior server assignments, and the addition of $n^{th}$ server only causes $1/n$ fraction of the BLOBs to relocate.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Although the process of moving BLOBs across cache servers in the cluster depends on the context, commonly, the newly added cache server identifies its "predecessor" and moves all the BLOBs, whose mapping belongs to this server (i.e. whose hash value is less than that of the new server), from it.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] However, in the case of web page caches, in most implementations there is no involvement of moving or copying, assuming the cached BLOB is small enough.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] When a request hits a newly added cache server, a cache miss happens and a request to the actual web server is made and the BLOB is cached locally for future requests.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] The redundant BLOBs on the previously used cache servers would be removed as per the cache eviction policies.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Let $h_{b}(x)$ and $h_{s}(x)$ be the hash functions used for the BLOB and server's unique identifier respectively.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] In practice, a binary search tree (BST) is used to dynamically maintain the ${\text{server ID}}$ within a cluster or hashring, and to find the successor or minimum within the BST, tree traversal is used.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] To avoid skewness of multiple nodes within the radian, which happen due to lack of uniform distribution of the servers within the cluster, multiple labels are used.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Those duplicate labels are called "virtual nodes" i.e. multiple labels which point to a single "real" label or server within the cluster.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] The amount of virtual nodes or duplicate labels used for a particular server within a cluster is called the "weight" of that particular server.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] A number of extensions to the basic technique are needed for effectively using consistent hashing for load balancing in practice.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] In the basic scheme above, if a server fails, all its BLOBs are reassigned to the next server in clockwise order, potentially doubling the load of that server.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] To ensure a more even redistribution of BLOBs on server failure, each server can be hashed to multiple locations on the unit circle.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] When a server fails, the BLOBs assigned to each of its replicas on the unit circle will get reassigned to a different server in clockwise order, thus redistributing the BLOBs more evenly.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Another extension concerns a situation where a single BLOB gets "hot" and is accessed a large number of times and will have to be hosted in multiple servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] In this situation, the BLOB may be assigned to multiple contiguous servers by traversing the unit circle in clockwise order.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] A more complex practical consideration arises when two BLOBs are hashed near each other in the unit circle and both get "hot" at the same time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] In this case, both BLOBs will use the same set of contiguous servers in the unit circle.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] This situation can be ameliorated by each BLOB choosing a different hash function for mapping servers to the unit circle.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique, and permits fully distributed agreement on a set of k options out of a possible set of n options.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] It can in fact be shown that consistent hashing is a special case of rendezvous hashing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] Because of its simplicity and generality, rendezvous hashing is now being used in place of Consistent Hashing in many applications.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] If key values will always increase monotonically, an alternative approach using a hash table with monotonic keys may be more suitable than consistent hashing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/consistent-hashing] The $O(K/N)$ is an average cost for redistribution of keys and the $O(\log N)$ complexity for consistent hashing comes from the fact that a binary search among nodes angles is required to find the next node on the ring.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] A **distributed hash table** (**DHT**) is a distributed system that provides a lookup service similar to a hash table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Key–value pairs are stored in a DHT, and any participating node can efficiently retrieve the value associated with a given key.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] The main advantage of a DHT is that nodes can be added or removed with minimum work around re-distributing keys.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] *Keys* are unique identifiers which map to particular *values*, which in turn can be anything from addresses, to documents, to arbitrary data.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Responsibility for maintaining the mapping from keys to values is distributed among the nodes, in such a way that a change in the set of participants causes a minimal amount of disruption.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] This allows a DHT to scale to extremely large numbers of nodes and to handle continual node arrivals, departures, and failures.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] DHTs form an infrastructure that can be used to build more complex services, such as anycast, cooperative web caching, distributed file systems, domain name services, instant messaging, multicast, and also peer-to-peer file sharing and content distribution systems.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Notable distributed networks that use DHTs include BitTorrent's distributed tracker, the Kad network, the Storm botnet, the Tox instant messenger, Freenet, the YaCy search engine, and the InterPlanetary File System.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] DHT research was originally motivated, in part, by peer-to-peer (P2P) systems such as Freenet, Gnutella, BitTorrent and Napster, which took advantage of resources distributed across the Internet to provide a single useful application.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] In particular, they took advantage of increased bandwidth and hard disk capacity to provide a file-sharing service.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] These systems differed in how they located the data offered by their peers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Napster, the first large-scale P2P content delivery system, required a central index server: each node, upon joining, would send a list of locally held files to the server, which would perform searches and refer the queries to the nodes that held the results.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] This central component left the system vulnerable to attacks and lawsuits.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Gnutella and similar networks moved to a query flooding model – in essence, each search would result in a message being broadcast to every machine in the network.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] While avoiding a single point of failure, this method was significantly less efficient than Napster.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Later versions of Gnutella clients moved to a dynamic querying model which vastly improved efficiency.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Freenet is fully distributed, but employs a heuristic key-based routing in which each file is associated with a key, and files with similar keys tend to cluster on a similar set of nodes.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Queries are likely to be routed through the network to such a cluster without needing to visit many peers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] However, Freenet does not guarantee that data will be found.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Distributed hash tables use a more structured key-based routing in order to attain both the decentralization of Freenet and Gnutella, and the efficiency and guaranteed results of Napster.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] One drawback is that, like Freenet, DHTs only directly support exact-match search, rather than keyword search, although Freenet's routing algorithm can be generalized to any key type where a closeness operation can be defined.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] In 2001, four systems—CAN, Chord, Pastry, and Tapestry—brought attention to DHTs.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] A project called the Infrastructure for Resilient Internet Systems (Iris) was funded by a $12 million grant from the United States National Science Foundation in 2002.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Researchers included Sylvia Ratnasamy, Ion Stoica, Hari Balakrishnan and Scott Shenker.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Outside academia, DHT technology has been adopted as a component of BitTorrent and in PlanetLab projects such as the Coral Content Distribution Network.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] A key technique used to achieve these goals is that any one node needs to coordinate with only a few other nodes in the system‍— most commonly, O(log *n*) of the *n* participants (see below)‍— so that only a limited amount of work needs to be done for each change in membership.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Some DHT designs seek to be secure against malicious participants and to allow participants to remain anonymous, though this is less common than in many other peer-to-peer (especially file sharing) systems; see anonymous P2P.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] The structure of a DHT can be decomposed into several main components.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] The foundation is an abstract keyspace, such as the set of 160-bit strings.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] A keyspace partitioning scheme splits ownership of this keyspace among the participating nodes.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] An overlay network then connects the nodes, allowing them to find the owner of any given key in the keyspace.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Once these components are in place, a typical use of the DHT for storage and retrieval might proceed as follows.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Suppose the keyspace is the set of 160-bit strings.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] To index a file with given filename and data in the DHT, the SHA-1 hash of filename is generated, producing a 160-bit key k, and a message *put*(*k, data*) is sent to any node participating in the DHT.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] The message is forwarded from node to node through the overlay network until it reaches the single node responsible for key k as specified by the keyspace partitioning.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] That node then stores the key and the data.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Any other client can then retrieve the contents of the file by again hashing filename to produce k and asking any DHT node to find the data associated with k with a message *get*(*k*).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] The message will again be routed through the overlay to the node responsible for k, which will reply with the stored data.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] The keyspace partitioning and overlay network components are described below with the goal of capturing the principal ideas common to most DHTs; many designs differ in the details.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Most DHTs use some variant of consistent hashing or rendezvous hashing to map keys to nodes.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] The two algorithms appear to have been devised independently and simultaneously to solve the distributed hash table problem.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Both consistent hashing and rendezvous hashing have the essential property that removal or addition of one node changes only the set of keys owned by the nodes with adjacent IDs, and leaves all other nodes unaffected.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Contrast this with a traditional hash table in which addition or removal of one bucket causes nearly the entire keyspace to be remapped.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Since any change in ownership typically corresponds to bandwidth-intensive movement of objects stored in the DHT from one node to another, minimizing such reorganization is required to efficiently support high rates of churn (node arrival and failure).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Consistent hashing employs a function $\delta (k_{1},k_{2})$ that defines an abstract notion of the distance between the keys $k_{1}$ and $k_{2}$ , which is unrelated to geographical distance or network latency.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Each node is assigned a single key called its *identifier* (ID).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] A node with ID $i_{x}$ owns all the keys $k_{m}$ for which $i_{x}$ is the closest ID, measured according to $\delta (k_{m},i_{x})$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] For example, the Chord DHT uses consistent hashing, which treats nodes as points on a circle, and $\delta (k_{1},k_{2})$ is the distance traveling clockwise around the circle from $k_{1}$ to $k_{2}$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Thus, the circular keyspace is split into contiguous segments whose endpoints are the node identifiers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] If $i_{1}$ and $i_{2}$ are two adjacent IDs, with a shorter clockwise distance from $i_{1}$ to $i_{2}$ , then the node with ID $i_{2}$ owns all the keys that fall between $i_{1}$ and $i_{2}$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] In rendezvous hashing, also called highest random weight (HRW) hashing, all clients use the same hash function $h()$ (chosen ahead of time) to associate a key to one of the *n* available servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Each client has the same list of identifiers {*S*1, *S*2, ..., *S**n* }, one for each server.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] The client associates that key with the server corresponding to the highest hash weight for that key.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] A server with ID $S_{x}$ owns all the keys $k_{m}$ for which the hash weight $h(S_{x},k_{m})$ is higher than the hash weight of any other node for that key.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Locality-preserving hashing ensures that similar keys are assigned to similar objects.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] This can enable a more efficient execution of range queries, however, in contrast to using consistent hashing, there is no more assurance that the keys (and thus the load) is uniformly randomly distributed over the key space and the participating peers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] DHT protocols such as Self-Chord and Oscar address such issues.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Self-Chord decouples object keys from peer IDs and sorts keys along the ring with a statistical approach based on the swarm intelligence paradigm.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Sorting ensures that similar keys are stored by neighbour nodes and that discovery procedures, including range queries, can be performed in logarithmic time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Oscar constructs a navigable small-world network based on random walk sampling also assuring logarithmic search time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Each node maintains a set of links to other nodes (its *neighbors* or routing table).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Together, these links form the overlay network.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] A node picks its neighbors according to a certain structure, called the network's topology.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] All DHT topologies share some variant of the most essential property: for any key k, each node either has a node ID that owns k or has a link to a node whose node ID is *closer* to k, in terms of the keyspace distance defined above.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] It is then easy to route a message to the owner of any key k using the following greedy algorithm (that is not necessarily globally optimal): at each step, forward the message to the neighbor whose ID is closest to k.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] When there is no such neighbor, then we must have arrived at the closest node, which is the owner of k as defined above.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] This style of routing is sometimes called key-based routing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Of course, having shorter routes requires higher maximum degree.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] The most common choice, $O(\log n)$ degree/route length, is not optimal in terms of degree/route length tradeoff, but such topologies typically allow more flexibility in choice of neighbors.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Many DHTs use that flexibility to pick neighbors that are close in terms of latency in the physical underlying network.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] In general, all DHTs construct navigable small-world network topologies, which trade-off route length vs. network degree.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Maximum route length is closely related to diameter: the maximum number of hops in any shortest path between nodes.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Clearly, the network's worst case route length is at least as large as its diameter, so DHTs are limited by the degree/diameter tradeoff that is fundamental in graph theory.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Route length can be greater than diameter, since the greedy routing algorithm may not find shortest paths.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Aside from routing, there exist many algorithms that exploit the structure of the overlay network for sending a message to all nodes, or a subset of nodes, in a DHT.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] These algorithms are used by applications to do overlay multicast, range queries, or to collect statistics.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Two systems that are based on this approach are Structella, which implements flooding and random walks on a Pastry overlay, and DQ-DHT, which implements a dynamic querying search algorithm over a Chord network.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Because of the decentralization, fault tolerance, and scalability of DHTs, they are inherently more resilient against a hostile attacker than a centralized system.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Open systems for distributed data storage that are robust against massive hostile attackers are feasible.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] A DHT system that is carefully designed to have Byzantine fault tolerance can defend against a security weakness, known as the Sybil attack, which affects most current DHT designs.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Whanau is a DHT designed to be resistant to Sybil attacks.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Petar Maymounkov, one of the original authors of Kademlia, has proposed a way to circumvent the weakness to the Sybil attack by incorporating social trust relationships into the system design.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] The new system, codenamed Tonika or also known by its domain name as 5ttt, is based on an algorithm design known as "electric routing" and co-authored with the mathematician Jonathan Kelner.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] Maymounkov has now undertaken a comprehensive implementation effort of this new system.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/distributed-hash-table] However, research into effective defences against Sybil attacks is generally considered an open question, and wide variety of potential defences are proposed every year in top security research conferences.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In computer science, a **hash table** is a data structure that implements an associative array, also called a **dictionary** or simply **map**; an associative array is an abstract data type that maps keys to values.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A hash table uses a hash function to compute an *index*, also called a *hash code*, into an array of *buckets* or *slots*, from which the desired value can be found.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] During lookup, the key is hashed and the resulting hash indicates where the corresponding value is stored.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A map implemented by a hash table is called a **hash map**.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Most hash table designs employ an imperfect hash function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Hash collisions, where the hash function generates the same index for more than one key, therefore typically must be accommodated in some way.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Common strategies to handle hash collisions include chaining, which stores multiple elements in the same slot using linked lists, and open addressing, which searches for the next available slot according to a probing sequence.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In a well-dimensioned hash table, the average time complexity for each lookup is independent of the number of elements stored in the table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Many hash table designs also allow arbitrary insertions and deletions of key–value pairs, at amortized constant average cost per operation.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Hashing is an example of a space–time tradeoff.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] If memory is infinite, the entire key can be used directly as an index to locate its value with a single memory access.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] On the other hand, if infinite time is available, values can be stored without regard for their keys, and a binary search or linear search can be used to retrieve the element.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In many situations, hash tables turn out to be on average more efficient than search trees or any other table lookup structure.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] For this reason, they are widely used in many kinds of computer software, particularly for associative arrays, database indexing, caches, and sets.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Many programming languages provide built-in hash table structures, such as Python’s dictionaries, Java’s HashMap, C++’s unordered_map, Go maps, which abstract the complexity of hashing from the programmer.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The idea of hashing arose independently in different places.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In January 1953, Hans Peter Luhn wrote an internal IBM memorandum that used hashing with chaining.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The first example of open addressing was proposed by A.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Around the same time, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research implemented hashing for the IBM 701 assembler.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Open addressing with linear probing is credited to Amdahl, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The term "open addressing" was coined by W.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Wesley Peterson in his article which discusses the problem of search in large files.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The first published work on hashing with chaining is credited to Arnold Dumey, who discussed the idea of using remainder modulo a prime as a hash function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The word "hashing" was first published in an article by Robert Morris.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A theoretical analysis of linear probing was submitted originally by Konheim and Weiss.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] An associative array stores a set of (key, value) pairs and allows insertion, deletion, and lookup (search), with the constraint of unique keys.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In the hash table implementation of associative arrays, an array A of length m is partially filled with n elements, where $m\geq n$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A key **x** is hashed using a hash function h to compute an index location $A[h(x)]$ in the hash table, where $h(x)<m$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The efficiency of a hash table depends on the load factor, defined as the ratio of the number of stored elements to the number of available slots, with lower load factors generally yielding faster operations.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] At this index, both the key and its associated value are stored.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Storing the key alongside the value ensures that lookups can verify the key at the index to retrieve the correct value, even in the presence of collisions.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Under reasonable assumptions, hash tables have better time complexity bounds on search, delete, and insert operations in comparison to self-balancing binary search trees.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Hash tables are also commonly used to implement sets, by omitting the stored value for each key and merely tracking whether the key is present.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The performance of the hash table deteriorates in relation to the load factor $\alpha$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In the limit of large m and n , each bucket statistically has a Poisson distribution with expectation $\lambda =\alpha$ for an ideally random hash function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The software typically ensures that the load factor $\alpha$ remains below a certain constant, $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Therefore, a common approach is to resize or "rehash" the hash table whenever the load factor $\alpha$ reaches $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Similarly the table may also be resized if the load factor drops below $\alpha _{\max }/4$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] With separate chaining hash tables, each slot of the bucket array stores a pointer to a list or array of data.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Separate chaining hash tables suffer gradually declining performance as the load factor grows, and no fixed point beyond which resizing is absolutely needed.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] With separate chaining, the value of $\alpha _{\max }$ that gives best performance is typically between 1 and 3.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] With open addressing, each slot of the bucket array holds exactly one item.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Therefore an open-addressed hash table cannot have a load factor greater than 1.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The performance of open addressing becomes very bad when the load factor approaches 1.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Therefore a hash table that uses open addressing *must* be resized or *rehashed* if the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] With open addressing, acceptable figures of max load factor $\alpha _{\max }$ should range around 0.6 to 0.75.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A hash function $h:U\rightarrow \{0,...,m-1\}$ maps the universe U of keys to indices or slots within the table, that is, $h(x)\in \{0,...,m-1\}$ for $x\in U$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The conventional implementations of hash functions are based on the *integer universe assumption* that all elements of the table stem from the universe $U=\{0,...,u-1\}$ , where the bit length of u is confined within the word size of a computer architecture.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A hash function h is said to be perfect for a given set S if it is injective on S , that is, if each element $x\in S$ maps to a different value in ${0,...,m-1}$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A perfect hash function can be created if all the keys are known ahead of time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The schemes of hashing used in *integer universe assumption* include hashing by division, hashing by multiplication, universal hashing, dynamic perfect hashing, and static perfect hashing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] However, hashing by division is the commonly used scheme.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by division is as follows: $h(x)\ =\ x\,{\bmod {\,}}m,$ where $h(x)$ is the hash value of $x\in S$ and m is the size of the table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by multiplication is as follows: $h(x)=\lfloor m{\bigl (}(xA){\bmod {1}}{\bigr )}\rfloor$ Where A is a non-integer real-valued constant and m is the size of the table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] An advantage of the hashing by multiplication is that the m is not critical.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Although any value A produces a hash function, Donald Knuth suggests using the golden ratio.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Commonly a string is used as a key to the hash function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The third edition of *The C++ Programming Language* describes a simple hash function in which an unsigned integer that is initially zero is repeatedly left shifted one bit and then xor'ed with the integer value of the next character.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] This hash value is then taken modulo the table size.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] If the left shift is not circular, then the string length should be at least eight bits less than the size of the unsigned integer in bits.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Another common way to hash a string to an integer is with a polynomial rolling hash function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Uniform distribution of the hash values is a fundamental requirement of a hash function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A non-uniform distribution increases the number of collisions and the cost of resolving them.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Uniformity is sometimes difficult to ensure by design, but may be evaluated empirically using statistical tests, e.g., a Pearson's chi-squared test for discrete uniform distributions.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The distribution needs to be uniform only for table sizes that occur in the application.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In particular, if one uses dynamic resizing with exact doubling and halving of the table size, then the hash function needs to be uniform only when the size is a power of two.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Here the index can be computed as some range of bits of the hash function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] On the other hand, some hashing algorithms prefer to have the size be a prime number.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] For open addressing schemes, the hash function should also avoid *runs*, the mapping of two or more keys to consecutive slots.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Such runs may cause the lookup cost to skyrocket, even if the load factor is low and collisions are infrequent.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The popular multiplicative hash is claimed to have particularly poor run behavior.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] K-independent hashing offers a way to prove a certain hash function does not have bad keysets for a given type of hashtable.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A number of K-independence results are known for collision resolution schemes such as linear probing and cuckoo hashing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Since K-independence can prove a hash function works, one can then focus on finding the fastest possible such hash function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A search algorithm that uses hashing consists of two parts.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The first part is computing a hash function which transforms the search key into an array index.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The ideal case is such that no two search keys hash to the same array index.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] However, this is not always the case and impossible to guarantee for unseen given data.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Hence the second part of the algorithm is collision resolution.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The two common methods for collision resolution are separate chaining and open addressing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In separate chaining, the process involves building a linked list with key–value pair for each search array index.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The collided items are chained together through a single linked list, which can be traversed to access the item with a unique search key.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Collision resolution through chaining with linked list is a common method of implementation of hash tables.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] If the element is comparable either numerically or lexically, and inserted into the list by maintaining the total order, it results in faster termination of the unsuccessful searches.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] If the keys are ordered, it could be efficient to use "self-organizing" concepts such as using a self-balancing binary search tree, through which the theoretical worst case could be brought down to $O(\log {n})$ , although it introduces additional complexities.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In dynamic perfect hashing, two-level hash tables are used to reduce the look-up complexity to be a guaranteed $O(1)$ in the worst case.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In this technique, the buckets of k entries are organized as perfect hash tables with $k^{2}$ slots providing constant worst-case lookup time, and low amortized time for insertion.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A study shows array-based separate chaining to be 97% more performant when compared to the standard linked list method under heavy load.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Techniques such as using fusion tree for each buckets also result in constant time for all operations with high probability.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The linked list of separate chaining implementation may not be cache-conscious due to spatial locality—locality of reference—when the nodes of the linked list are scattered across memory, thus the list traversal during insert and search may entail CPU cache inefficiencies.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Open addressing is another collision resolution technique in which every entry record is stored in the bucket array itself, and the hash resolution is performed through **probing**.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] When a new entry has to be inserted, the buckets are examined, starting with the hashed-to slot and proceeding in some *probe sequence*, until an unoccupied slot is found.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] When searching for an entry, the buckets are scanned in the same sequence, until either the target record is found, or an unused array slot is found, which indicates an unsuccessful search.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The performance of open addressing may be slower compared to separate chaining since the probe sequence increases when the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The probing results in an infinite loop if the load factor reaches 1, in the case of a completely filled table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The average cost of linear probing depends on the hash function's ability to distribute the elements uniformly throughout the table to avoid runs, since formation of runs would result in increased search time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Since the slots are located in successive locations, linear probing could lead to better utilization of CPU cache due to locality of references resulting in reduced memory latency.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Coalesced hashing is a hybrid of both separate chaining and open addressing in which the buckets or nodes link within the table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The algorithm is ideally suited for fixed memory allocation.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The collision in coalesced hashing is resolved by identifying the largest-indexed empty slot on the hash table, then the colliding value is inserted into that slot.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The bucket is also linked to the inserted node's slot which contains its colliding hash address.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Cuckoo hashing is a form of open addressing collision resolution technique which guarantees $O(1)$ worst-case lookup complexity and constant amortized time for insertions.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The collision is resolved through maintaining two hash tables, each having its own hashing function, and collided slot gets replaced with the given item, and the preoccupied element of the slot gets displaced into the other hash table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The process continues until every key has its own spot in the empty buckets of the tables; if the procedure enters into infinite loop—which is identified through maintaining a threshold loop counter—both hash tables get rehashed with newer hash functions and the procedure continues.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Hopscotch hashing is an open addressing based algorithm which combines the elements of cuckoo hashing, linear probing and chaining through the notion of a *neighbourhood* of buckets—the subsequent buckets around any given occupied bucket, also called a "virtual" bucket.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The algorithm is designed to deliver better performance when the load factor of the hash table grows beyond 90%; it also provides high throughput in concurrent settings, thus well suited for implementing resizable concurrent hash table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Each bucket within the hash table includes an additional "hop-information"—an *H*-bit bit array for indicating the relative distance of the item which was originally hashed into the current virtual bucket within *H* − 1 entries.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] *H* − 1, subsequent swap and hop-info bit array manipulation of each bucket is performed in accordance with its neighbourhood invariant properties.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Robin Hood hashing is an open addressing based collision resolution algorithm; the collisions are resolved through favouring the displacement of the element that is farthest—or longest *probe sequence length* (PSL)—from its "home location" i.e. the bucket to which the item was hashed into.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] It is named after Robin Hood, a mythical heroic outlaw who stole from the rich to give to the poor.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Although Robin Hood hashing does not change the theoretical search cost, it significantly affects the variance of the distribution of the items on the buckets, i.e. dealing with long run formation in the hash table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Each node within the hash table that uses Robin Hood hashing should be augmented to store an extra PSL value.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] If a hash table becomes "too empty" after deleting some elements, resizing may be performed to avoid excessive memory usage.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Generally, a new hash table with a size double that of the original hash table gets allocated privately and every item in the original hash table gets moved to the newly allocated one by computing the hash values of the items followed by the insertion operation.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Rehashing is simple, but computationally expensive.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Some hash table implementations, notably in real-time systems, cannot pay the price of enlarging the hash table all at once, because it may interrupt time-critical operations.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] If one cannot avoid dynamic resizing, a solution is to perform the resizing gradually to avoid storage blip—typically at 50% of new table's size—during rehashing and to avoid memory fragmentation that triggers heap compaction due to deallocation of large memory blocks caused by the old hash table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In such case, the rehashing operation is done incrementally through extending prior memory block allocated for the old hash table such that the buckets of the hash table remain unaltered.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A common approach for amortized rehashing involves maintaining two hash functions $h_{\text{old}}$ and $h_{\text{new}}$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Linear hashing is an implementation of the hash table which enables dynamic growths or shrinks of the table one bucket at a time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The performance of a hash table is dependent on the hash function's ability in generating quasi-random numbers ( $\sigma$ ) for entries in the hash table where K , n and $h(x)$ denotes the key, number of buckets and the hash function such that $\sigma \ =\ h(K)\ \%\ n$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] If the hash function generates the same $\sigma$ for distinct keys ( $K_{1}\neq K_{2},\ h(K_{1})\ =\ h(K_{2})$ ), this results in *collision*, which is dealt with in a variety of ways.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The constant time complexity ( $O(1)$ ) of the operation in a hash table is presupposed on the condition that the hash function doesn't generate colliding indices; thus, the performance of the hash table is directly proportional to the chosen hash function's ability to disperse the indices.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] However, construction of such a hash function is practically infeasible, that being so, implementations depend on case-specific collision resolution techniques in achieving higher performance.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] The best performance is obtained in the case that the hash function distributes the elements of the universe uniformaly, and the elements stored at the table are drawn at random from the universe.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In this case, in hashing with chaining, the expected time for a successful search is ${\textstyle 1+{\frac {\alpha }{2}}+\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ , and the expected time for an unsuccessful search is ${\textstyle e^{-\alpha }+\alpha +\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Hash tables are commonly used to implement many types of in-memory tables.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] They are used to implement associative arrays.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Hash tables may also be used as disk-based data structures and database indices (such as in dbm) although B-trees are more popular in these applications.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Hash tables can be used to implement caches, auxiliary data tables that are used to speed up the access to data that is primarily stored in slower media.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] In this application, hash collisions can be handled by discarding one of the two colliding entries—usually erasing the old item that is currently stored in the table and overwriting it with the new item, so every item in the table has a unique hash value.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Hash tables can be used in the implementation of set data structure, which can store unique values without any particular order; set is typically used in testing the membership of a value in the collection, rather than element retrieval.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] A transposition table to a complex Hash Table which stores information about each section that has been searched.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/hash-table] Many programming languages provide hash table functionality, either as built-in associative arrays or as standard library modules.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Consistent hashing addresses the special case $k=1$ using a different method.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Rendezvous hashing is both much simpler and more general than consistent hashing (see below).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Rendezvous hashing was invented by David Thaler and Chinya Ravishankar at the University of Michigan in 1996.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Consistent hashing appeared a year later in the literature.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Given its simplicity and generality, rendezvous hashing is now being preferred to consistent hashing in real-world applications.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Rendezvous hashing was used very early on in many applications including mobile caching, router design, secure key establishment, and sharding and distributed databases.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] One of the first applications of rendezvous hashing was to enable multicast clients on the Internet (in contexts such as the MBONE) to identify multicast rendezvous points in a distributed fashion.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] It was used in 1998 by Microsoft's Cache Array Routing Protocol (CARP) for distributed cache coordination and routing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Some Protocol Independent Multicast routing protocols use rendezvous hashing to pick a rendezvous point.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Rendezvous hashing solves a general version of the distributed hash table problem: We are given a set of n sites (servers or proxies, say).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] How can any set of clients, given an object O , agree on a *k-*subset of sites to assign to O ?
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The standard version of the problem uses *k = 1.* Each client is to make its selection independently, but all clients must end up picking the same subset of sites.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] This is non-trivial if we add a *minimal disruption* constraint, and require that when a site fails or is removed, only objects mapping to that site need be reassigned to other sites.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The basic idea is to give each site $S_{j}$ a score (a *weight*) for each object $O_{i}$ , and assign the object to the highest scoring site.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] All clients first agree on a hash function $h(\cdot )$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Each client independently computes these weights $w_{i,1},w_{i,2}\dots w_{i,n}$ and picks the *k* sites that yield the *k* largest hash values.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The clients have thereby achieved distributed k -agreement.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If a site S is added or removed, only the objects mapping to S are remapped to different sites, satisfying the minimal disruption constraint above.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The HRW assignment can be computed independently by any client, since it depends only on the identifiers for the set of sites $S_{1},S_{2}\dots S_{n}$ and the object being assigned.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] HRW easily accommodates different capacities among sites.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If site $S_{k}$ has twice the capacity of the other sites, we simply represent $S_{k}$ twice in the list, say, as $S_{k,1},S_{k,2}$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Clearly, twice as many objects will now map to $S_{k}$ as to the other sites.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Consider the simple version of the problem, with *k = 1,* where all clients are to agree on a single site for an object *O.* Approaching the problem naively, it might appear sufficient to treat the *n* sites as buckets in a hash table and hash the object name *O* into this table.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Unfortunately, if any of the sites fails or is unreachable, the hash table size changes, forcing all objects to be remapped.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] This massive disruption makes such direct hashing unworkable.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Under rendezvous hashing, however, clients handle site failures by picking the site that yields the next largest weight.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Remapping is required only for objects currently mapped to the failed site, and disruption is minimal.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] **Load balancing:** Since the hash function is randomizing, each of the *n*sites is equally likely to receive the object *O*.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] **High hit rate:** Since all clients agree on placing an object *O* into the same site *SO*, each fetch or placement of *O* into *SO* yields the maximum utility in terms of hit rate.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The object *O* will always be found unless it is evicted by some replacement algorithm at *SO*.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] **Minimal disruption:** When a site fails, only the objects mapped to that site need to be remapped.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Disruption is at the minimal possible level.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] **Distributed *k*-agreement:** Clients can reach distributed agreement on *k* sites simply by selecting the top *k* sites in the ordering.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The standard version of Rendezvous Hashing described above works quite well for moderate *n,* but when n is extremely large, the hierarchical use of Rendezvous Hashing achieves $O(\log n)$ running time.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] This approach creates a virtual hierarchical structure (called a "skeleton"), and achieves $O(\log n)$ running time by applying HRW at each level while descending the hierarchy.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] In the accompanying diagram, the cluster size is $m=4$ , and the skeleton fanout is $f=3$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Assuming 108 sites (real nodes) for convenience, we get a three-tier virtual hierarchy.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Since $f=3$ , each virtual node has a natural numbering in octal.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Thus, the 27 virtual nodes at the lowest tier would be numbered $000,001,002,...,221,222$ in octal (we can, of course, vary the fanout at each level - in that case, each node will be identified with the corresponding mixed-radix number).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The easiest way to understand the virtual hierarchy is by starting at the top, and descending the virtual hierarchy.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] We successively apply Rendezvous Hashing to the set of virtual nodes at each level of the hierarchy, and descend the branch defined by the winning virtual node.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] We can in fact start at any level in the virtual hierarchy.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Starting lower in the hierarchy requires more hashes, but may improve load distribution in the case of failures.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] For example, instead of applying HRW to all 108 real nodes in the diagram, we can first apply HRW to the 27 lowest-tier virtual nodes, selecting one.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] We then apply HRW to the four real nodes in its cluster, and choose the winning site.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If we apply this method starting one level higher in the hierarchy, we would need $9+3+4=16$ hashes to get to the winning site.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The figure shows how, if we proceed starting from the root of the skeleton, we may successively choose the virtual nodes $(2)_{3}$ , $(20)_{3}$ , and $(200)_{3}$ , and finally end up with site 74.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The virtual hierarchy need not be stored, but can be created on demand, since the virtual nodes names are simply prefixes of base- f (or mixed-radix) representations.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] We can easily create appropriately sorted strings from the digits, as required.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Clearly, T has height $h=O(\log c)=O(\log n)$ , since m and f are both constants.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The work done at each level is $O(1)$ , since f is a constant.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The value of m can be chosen based on factors like the anticipated failure rate and the degree of desired load balancing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] A higher value of m leads to less load skew in the event of failure at the cost of higher search overhead.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The choice $m=n$ is equivalent to non-hierarchical rendezvous hashing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] In practice, the hash function $h(\cdot )$ is very cheap, so $m=n$ can work quite well unless n is very high.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] For any given object, it is clear that each leaf-level cluster, and hence each of the n sites, is chosen with equal probability.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] One can enhance resiliency to failures by replicating each object *O* across the highest ranking *r < m* sites for *O,* choosing *r* based on the level of resiliency desired.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The simplest strategy is to replicate only within the leaf-level cluster.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If the leaf-level site selected for *O* is unavailable, we select the next-ranked site for *O* within the same leaf-level cluster.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If *O* has been replicated within the leaf-level cluster, we are sure to find *O* in the next available site in the ranked order of *r* sites.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] All objects that were held by the failed server appear in some other site in its cluster.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] (Another option is to go up one or more tiers in the skeleton and select an alternate from among the sibling virtual nodes at that tier.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] When a site is added to the system, it may become the winning site for some objects already assigned to other sites.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Objects mapped to other clusters will never map to this new site, so we need to only consider objects held by other sites in its cluster.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If the sites are caches, attempting to access an object mapped to the new site will result in a cache miss, the corresponding object will be fetched and cached, and operation returns to normal.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If sites are servers, some objects must be remapped to this newly added site.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] As before, objects mapped to other clusters will never map to this new site, so we need to only consider objects held by sites in its cluster.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] That is, we need only remap objects currently present in the *m* sites in this local cluster, rather than the entire set of objects in the system.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] New objects mapping to this site will of course be automatically assigned to it.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Because of its simplicity, lower overhead, and generality (it works for any *k < n*), rendezvous hashing is increasingly being preferred over consistent hashing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Recent examples of its use include the GitHub load balancer, the Apache Ignite distributed database, and by the Twitter EventBus pub/sub platform.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Consistent hashing operates by mapping each site uniformly and randomly to multiple points on a unit circle called tokens.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Objects are also mapped to the unit circle and placed in the site owning the token that is first encountered traveling clockwise from the object's location.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] When a site is removed, each of its objects is transferred to the site owning the next token encountered moving clockwise.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Provided each site is mapped to a large number of tokens (100–200, say), this will reassign objects in a relatively uniform fashion among the remaining sites.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If a site's tokens are placed on the unit circle by hashing 200 variants of the site ID, say, then the assignment of any object requires storing or recalculating 200 hash values for each site.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] However, the tokens associated with a given site can be precomputed and stored in a sorted list, requiring only a single application of the hash function to the object, and a binary search to compute the assignment.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Even with many tokens per site, however, the basic version of consistent hashing may not balance objects uniformly over sites, since when a site is removed each object assigned to it is distributed only over as many other sites as the site has tokens (say 100–200).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Variants of consistent hashing (such as Amazon's Dynamo) that use more complex logic to distribute tokens on the unit circle offer better load balancing than basic consistent hashing, reduce the overhead of adding new sites, and reduce metadata overhead and offer other benefits.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Rendezvous hashing (HRW) is much simpler conceptually and in practice.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] It also distributes objects uniformly over all sites, given a uniform hash function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Unlike consistent hashing, HRW requires no precomputing or storage of tokens.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Consider *k =1.* An object $O_{i}$ is placed into one of n sites $S_{1},S_{2}\dots S_{n}$ by computing the n hash values $h(O_{i},S_{j})$ and picking the site $S_{k}$ that yields the highest hash value.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If a new site $S_{n+1}$ is added, new object placements or requests will compute $n+1$ hash values, and pick the largest of these.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If an object already in the system at $S_{k}$ maps to this new site $S_{n+1}$ , it will be fetched afresh and cached at $S_{n+1}$ .
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] All clients will henceforth obtain it from this site, and the old cached copy at $S_{k}$ will ultimately be replaced by the local cache management algorithm.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If $S_{k}$ is taken offline, its objects will be remapped uniformly to the remaining $n-1$ sites.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Variants of the HRW algorithm, such as the use of a skeleton (see below), can reduce the $O(n)$ time for object location to $O(\log n)$ , at the cost of less global uniformity of placement.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] When n is not too large, however, the $O(n)$ placement cost of basic HRW is not likely to be a problem.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] HRW completely avoids all the overhead and complexity associated with correctly handling multiple tokens for each site and associated metadata.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Rendezvous hashing also has the great advantage that it provides simple solutions to other important problems, such as distributed k -agreement.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Rendezvous hashing is both simpler and more general than consistent hashing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Consistent hashing can be shown to be a special case of HRW by an appropriate choice of a two-place hash function.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] From the site identifier S the simplest version of consistent hashing computes a list of token positions, e.g., $t_{s}=h_{c}(S)$ where $h_{c}$ hashes values to locations on the unit circle.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] This will duplicate exactly the assignment produced by consistent hashing.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] It is not possible, however, to reduce HRW to consistent hashing (assuming the number of tokens per site is bounded), since HRW potentially reassigns the objects from a removed site to an unbounded number of other sites.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] In the standard implementation of rendezvous hashing, every node receives a statically equal proportion of the keys.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] This behavior, however, is undesirable when the nodes have different capacities for processing or holding their assigned keys.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] For example, if one of the nodes had twice the storage capacity as the others, it would be beneficial if the algorithm could take this into account such that this more powerful node would receive twice the number of keys as each of the others.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] A straightforward mechanism to handle this case is to assign two virtual locations to this node, so that if either of that larger node's virtual locations has the highest hash, that node receives the key.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] But this strategy does not work when the relative weights are not integer multiples.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] For example, if one node had 42% more storage capacity, it would require adding many virtual nodes in different proportions, leading to greatly reduced performance.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Several modifications to rendezvous hashing have been proposed to overcome this limitation.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The Cache Array Routing Protocol (CARP) is a 1998 IETF draft that describes a method for computing *load factors* which can be multiplied by each node's hash score to yield an arbitrary level of precision for weighting nodes differently.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] However, one disadvantage of this approach is that when any node's weight is changed, or when any node is added or removed, all the load factors must be re-computed and relatively scaled.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] When the load factors change relative to one another, it triggers movement of keys between nodes whose weight was not changed, but whose load factor did change relative to other nodes in the system.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] This results in excess movement of keys.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Controlled replication under scalable hashing or CRUSH is an extension to RUSH that improves upon rendezvous hashing by constructing a tree where a pseudo-random function (hash) is used to navigate down the tree to find which node is ultimately responsible for a given key.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] It permits perfect stability for adding nodes; however, it is not perfectly stable when removing or re-weighting nodes, with the excess movement of keys being proportional to the height of the tree.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] The CRUSH algorithm is used by the ceph data storage system to map data objects to the nodes responsible for storing them.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] In 2005, Christian Schindelhauer and Gunnar Schomaker described a logarithmic method for re-weighting hash scores in a way that does not require relative scaling of load factors when a node's weight changes or when nodes are added or removed.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] This enabled the dual benefits of perfect precision when weighting nodes, along with perfect stability, as only a minimum number of keys needed to be remapped to new nodes.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] A similar logarithm-based hashing strategy is used to assign data to storage nodes in Cleversafe's data storage system, now IBM Cloud Object Storage.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Rendezvous hashing is being used widely in real-world systems.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Implementation is straightforward once a hash function $h(\cdot )$ is chosen (the original work on the HRW method makes a hash function recommendation).
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Each client only needs to compute a hash value for each of the n sites, and then pick the largest.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] If the hash function is efficient, the $O(n)$ running time is not a problem unless n is very large.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] A logarithmic transformation of the uniform score (unit interval) is applied, when multiplied by the node weights the probability of a node winning is proportional to its weight relative to the total weight of all nodes.
[src:consistent-hashing-algo/rendezvous-hashing] Note the magnitude of the scores vary greatly but the probabilities remain constant.
